Introduction¶

Formula One, also known as F1, is an international competition where high class open-wheel single-seater formula cars race against each other to see which automobile constructed can cross the finish line first after a given number of laps around a track. Drivers get points for the position that they finish in (higher points are given to those who finish the race course fastest). At the end of the season, the driver with the most points is crowned as the World Champion.

Our team was interested in observing which nationalities tend to gather the most amount of points over the years, so we took a look at different datasets-such as the drivers, results, and races files-to help us come up with the results for this insight. After loading different datasets, however, we noticed that some of these data either lacked information to give us accurate results or needed to be filtered to remove skewed results. Through merging, aggregating, and subsetting, the team was able to find the annual average points for the top 10 nationalities over the years and display the overall average points for these nationalities. These data cleaning processes allowed us to gather results from constructors that have been participating in F1 for more than 30 years. The results show that there are definite fluctuations of average points of top nationalities over time, but ultimately the Finnish are ranked at the top.

Dataset tables¶

For our project we used the drivers, results, races, and qualifying tables.

The drivers table contains 9 variables -- driverId, driverRef, number, code, forename, surname, dob, nationality, and url. It contains basic biographical information on each driver, with each row representing a single driver.

The results table contains 18 variables -- resultId, raceId, constructorId, number, grid, position, positionText, positionOrder, points, laps, time, milliseconds, fastestLap, rank, fastestLapTime, fastestLapSpeed, statusId. Each row represents each driver's performance in every race they participated in, with one row per race.

The races table contains 18 variables -- raceId, year, round, circuitId, name, date, time, url, fp1_date, fp1_time, fp2_date, fp2_time, fp3_date, fp3_time, quali_date, quali_time, sprint_date, sprint_time. It contains information on when and where each race occurred, with each row representing one race.

The qualifying table contains 9 variables -- qualifyId, raceId, driverId, constructorId, number, position, q1, q2, and q3. It contains information on each driver's performance in the qualifying rounds for each race, with each row representing one driver's performance.

qualifying = pd.read_csv("data_raw/qualifying.csv").rename(columns = {"position": "qualifying_position"})

Data Cleaning¶

To select relevant columns, a list of column names is first defined and all columns not contained in that list are excluded form the raw dataframes before merging. Later, when creating line charts that plot the trends in national average points over time, countries with less than 30 data points (i.e. less than 30 rows) are dropped from the dataframe. This is accomplished by first counting the number of rows of each country, creating a set of countries named complete_countries that have more than 30 rows and filtering out all countries that are not contained in the list.

Columns Selected¶

Two columns "raceId" and "driverId" are used for merging the data frames since they are shared by many individual dataframes. Columns "year", "nationality", and "qualifying_position" are selected as independent variables to explain change in our response variable "points". Specifically, qualifying position determines the position each driver starts in the race, and drivers who performed well in the qualifying round would be granted better qualifying positions. Point is the score offered to players after each game based on their finishing position. Points are accumulated over time and the player and the team with most points would be named champion.

In [ ]:
relevant_columns = ["raceId", "driverId", "year", "nationality", "qualifying_position", "points"]
races = races[races.columns.intersection(relevant_columns)]
results = results[results.columns.intersection(relevant_columns)]
drivers = drivers[drivers.columns.intersection(relevant_columns)]
qualifying = qualifying[qualifying.columns.intersection(relevant_columns)]

Merge Datasets¶

In [ ]:
races_results_merged = pd.merge(races, results,
                            on = "raceId",
                            how = "left")
mega_merged = pd.merge(races_results_merged, drivers,
                       on = "driverId",
                       how = "left")
mega_merged = pd.merge(mega_merged, qualifying,
                                        on = ["raceId", "driverId"], 
                                        how = "left")

Unsuccessful Graphs¶

In the following section we display some unsuccessful attempts at visualizing data. Graph 1 looks highly untidy and disorganized because we attempted to display data for all 10 countries in one plot, which is apparently too much to fit in one plot. Also, as you can see from the second graph, the graphs display messy line plots of average points over the years. This is due to some nationalities racking up high points, but only racing for a short amount of time. The Polish and Colombian, for example, show results for only certain years because they have not raced in other years. This did not provide us with results of the top 10 nationalities with the highest average points over the years of F1, so we wanted to filter this dataset a bit more.

    ax[row, col].plot("year", "avg_points", data = subset)

                                             avg_positions = ("qualifying_position", "mean")))
average_points_positions.dropna(inplace = True)

Successful Plot 3: Correlation between Qualifying Position and Point¶

This graph shows that there is correlation between the qualifying positions and the points that each nationality received on average. This means that the nationalities were able to have a better ranking, and one cause of them having the points that they do is because of the qualifying position that they had. However, We also know that the qualifying positions are due to how good the drivers do in the qualifying race. Therefore, we can say that if the drivers do well in the qualifying race then they are more likely to also do well in the race.

In [ ]:
x_data = average_points_positions["avg_points"]
y_data = average_points_positions["avg_positions"]


plt.scatter(x_data, y_data)
a, b = np.polyfit(x_data, y_data, 1)
corr = round(pearsonr(x_data, y_data)[0], 3)
pval = round(pearsonr(x_data, y_data)[1], 3)
plt.plot(x_data, x_data * a + b, color = "red")
plt.xlabel("National Average Qualifying Position")
plt.ylabel("National Average Point")
plt.title("Correlation between Qualifying Position and Point")
plt.legend([f"Corr = {corr} \n P-val = {pval}"])

Discussion¶

After filtering the dataset to keep countries that have raced for more than 30 years, the team found different results. This time, the Finnish ranked first with 2.94 average points over the years and there has been some major changes to the ranking of other countries as well. Overall, our findings support that sufficient data points is necessary to obtain an accurate picture of countries' performance as the occasional success of some countries might overshadow the high performance of countries that consistently do well.
